# French National Assembly Dataset Pipeline

This repository builds and documents a French National Assembly dataset used for
speech-level political analysis. It combines:

- DILA open-data debate XML files for 2011-2026;
- ParisParl historical debate files for 1998-2010 in the final merged speech
  table;
- Assemblee nationale and Sycomore deputy data;
- manually curated party mappings;
- PostgreSQL import scripts and a LaTeX technical report.

The descriptive dataset report is available in:

- `doc/dataset_report.tex`
- `doc/dataset_report.pdf`

This README is the technical entry point: it explains the repository layout,
the scripts, the main commands, and the expected outputs.

## Repository Layout

```text
.
|-- main.py                         # Repository-level CLI dispatcher
|-- convert_acteurs_to_csv.py        # Deputy and mandate generation pipeline
|-- data_aug.py                     # Compatibility entry point + small CSV augmentation helper
|-- mine_parisparl.py               # Notebook-exported ParisParl prototyping script
|-- dataset.md                      # Source notes used to write the report
|-- update.md                       # Dataset review notes and known issues
|-- converter/                      # DILA XML download/convert/CSV modules
|-- import_data/                    # DILA command-line orchestration
|-- eda/                            # ParisParl cleaning, entity binding, and notebooks
|-- data/                           # Raw, intermediate, and final data files
|-- deputes_boostrap/report/        # Audit reports generated by the deputy pipeline
|-- sql/                            # PostgreSQL schema/import helpers
|-- tests/                          # Unit tests for conversion and cleaning logic
`-- doc/                            # Dataset report and external documentation
```

## Requirements

The code is written for Python 3. The scripts use the Python standard library
plus common data packages used by the notebooks and EDA scripts, especially
`pandas` and `numpy`. Tests are written for `pytest`.

There is no pinned requirements file in the repository. For a fresh local
environment, install the minimum packages used by the scripts and tests:

```bash
python3 -m pip install pandas numpy pytest openpyxl
```

`openpyxl` is useful when inspecting or extending the Excel inputs stored in the
data folders.

The LaTeX report requires a working LaTeX installation with `latexmk`.

Network access is only needed for:

- downloading DILA archives;
- refreshing Sycomore pages in the deputy pipeline.

Most development and verification commands can run from the local files already
stored in the repository.

## Main Entry Point

`main.py` dispatches commands in two ways:

- if the first argument is `download`, `convert`, `csv`, or `all`, it runs the
  DILA speech import CLI from `import_data/main.py`;
- otherwise it runs the deputy and mandate pipeline from
  `convert_acteurs_to_csv.py`.

Examples:

```bash
# DILA speech pipeline
python3 main.py csv
python3 main.py all --years 2011-2026

# Deputy/mandate pipeline
python3 main.py --local-only --dry-run
python3 main.py --out-dir data/output
```

## Final Outputs

The most important generated or curated files are:

| File | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `data/final/speeches_1998_2026.csv` | Final compact speech table for 1998-2026. |
| `data/speech/2011_2026/centralized_speeches.csv` | Paragraph-level DILA CSV generated from converted XML. |
| `data/final/parisparl_speeches_1998_2010_processed.csv` | Cleaned ParisParl input used in the final merge. |
| `data/final/parisparl_speeches_1998_2019_processed.csv` | Extended processed ParisParl output. |
| `data/final/politician.csv` | Final politician reference table used by the project. |
| `data/final/mandate.csv` | Final mandate reference table used by the project. |
| `data/parties/party.csv` | Curated party and parliamentary group mapping. |
| `data/final/presidency.csv` | Presidency reference table for chair speeches. |

By default, `convert_acteurs_to_csv.py` writes regenerated deputy files to
`data/output`. Use `--out-dir data/final` only when you intentionally want to
refresh the final reference tables.

## DILA Speech Pipeline, 2011-2026

The DILA pipeline converts official open-data XML debate records into a
centralized CSV.

Source:

```text
https://echanges.dila.gouv.fr/OPENDATA/Debats/AN/
```

Default directories:

```text
data/speech/2011_2026/raw
data/speech/2011_2026/converted
data/speech/2011_2026/centralized_speeches.csv
```

Run the full pipeline:

```bash
python3 main.py all --years 2011-2026
```

If the XML files are already present locally and you only want to rebuild JSON
and CSV outputs:

```bash
python3 main.py all --skip-download
```

Run the steps separately:

```bash
python3 main.py download --years 2026
python3 main.py convert
python3 main.py csv
```

Useful options:

```bash
python3 main.py download --years 2024,2025,2026
python3 main.py download --years 2011-2026 --dry-run
python3 main.py download --years 2026 --force-download
python3 main.py convert --log-context-samples
python3 main.py csv --csv-file /tmp/centralized_speeches.csv
```

### DILA Modules

| Script | Role |
| --- | --- |
| `converter/download_dila_debats.py` | Reads the DILA index, finds archive links, downloads `.taz`, `.tar`, `.tar.gz`, or `.tgz` files, and safely extracts XML files. |
| `converter/convert.py` | Parses `CRI_*.xml` files into JSON files under `data/speech/2011_2026/converted`. It preserves source filenames, dates, session numbers, paragraph ids, speaker blocks, roles, and topic hierarchy. |
| `converter/json_to_csv.py` | Flattens converted JSON files into `centralized_speeches.csv`, one row per paragraph. |
| `import_data/main.py` | Provides the `download`, `convert`, `csv`, and `all` CLI commands. It also enriches converted JSON files with `numSeance` from raw XML when needed. |

The centralized DILA CSV schema is:

```text
source_files,id,date,text_speech_brut,text_speech_clean,topic,subtopic1,subtopic2,speaker,link_speaker,role,gender,speech_interjection,quote,numSeance
```

## ParisParl Historical Pipeline

ParisParl is used for historical debates before the DILA XML period.

Source:

```text
https://zenodo.org/records/3819374
```

Local yearly files are stored as:

```text
data/speech/1996_2019/parisparl_reden_YYYY.csv
```

The repository currently uses processed ParisParl data starting in 1998. The
1996-1997 gap is documented in `update.md` and `doc/dataset_report.tex`.

The ParisParl work is more exploratory than the DILA pipeline because the
source is reconstructed from PDF-derived text. The final processing logic lives
mostly in `eda/` modules and `eda/mine_parisparl.ipynb`.

Important files:

| File | Role |
| --- | --- |
| `mine_parisparl.py` | Notebook-exported prototype for debate structure recovery. Useful for understanding rules, not the cleanest CLI entry point. |
| `eda/mine_parisparl.ipynb` | Main notebook used to build and inspect processed ParisParl outputs and the final 1998-2026 merge. |
| `eda/summary_extraction.py` | Extracts the official `SOMMAIRE` zone and topic hierarchy. |
| `eda/title_cleaning.py` | Cleans French parliamentary title detokenization artifacts. |
| `eda/interjection_filter.py` | Distinguishes real parliamentary reactions from structural false positives. |
| `eda/speech_grouping.py` | Groups consecutive rows from the same speaker and attaches interjections. |
| `eda/entity_binding.py` | Binds speeches to `party.csv` and `politician.csv`. |

Processed outputs:

```text
data/final/parisparl_speeches_1998_2010_processed.csv
data/final/parisparl_speeches_1998_2019_processed.csv
```

The processed ParisParl schema is:

```text
speech_order,row_type,procedure_type,first_row_order,last_row_order,source_row_orders,source_ids,role,date,session,major_topic_order,major_topic,subtopic,speech_text,interjections,party_id,mp_id
```

## Final Speech Table, 1998-2026

The final compact speech table is:

```text
data/final/speeches_1998_2026.csv
```

Schema:

```text
speech_id,speech_text,speech_interjection,speech_date,speaker_id,country_id,term
```

It is built by combining:

- `data/final/parisparl_speeches_1998_2010_processed.csv`;
- `data/speech/2011_2026/centralized_speeches.csv`;
- `data/final/presidency.csv`.

The merge is performed in `eda/mine_parisparl.ipynb`. The notebook normalizes
the two sources, binds presidency rows, computes legislature terms, sorts rows
chronologically, and generates sequential `speech_id` values.

Final quality checks in the notebook verify that:

- the final column order matches the expected schema;
- `speech_id` is unique and monotonically increasing;
- `speech_date` is never missing;
- `speaker_id` is never empty after presidency binding;
- `country_id` is always `3`;
- `term` is never missing.

## Deputy and Mandate Pipeline

`convert_acteurs_to_csv.py` builds politician and mandate reference tables from
official Assemblee nationale JSON files and complementary Sycomore pages.

Primary local inputs:

```text
data/deputes/acteur
data/deputes/organe
data/parties/party.csv
```

Default outputs:

```text
data/output/politician.csv
data/output/mandate.csv
```

Run the full pipeline:

```bash
python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py
```

Run through the repository entry point:

```bash
python3 main.py
```

Check local JSON conversion without Sycomore and without writing files:

```bash
python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py --local-only --dry-run
```

Refresh the final reference tables intentionally:

```bash
python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py --out-dir data/final
```

Useful options:

```bash
python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py --terms 10,11
python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py --refresh-cache
python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py --party-csv data/parties/party.csv
python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py --report-dir deputes_boostrap/report
```

Available options:

```text
--actors-dir
--organs-dir
--out-dir
--country-id
--party-csv
--terms
--cache-dir
--delay
--refresh-cache
--dry-run
--local-only
--report-dir
```

### Deputy Pipeline Rules

- Local Assemblee nationale JSON rows take priority over Sycomore rows.
- Sycomore is used to add missing politicians or mandates for legislatures 10
  to 17.
- Politicians are deduplicated by `mp_id`.
- Mandates are deduplicated by `mp_id + term`.
- Existing `PA...` identifiers are preserved.
- If Sycomore has no usable `PA...` identifier, a deterministic fallback id is
  generated and written to an audit report.
- No `SYC...` identifier is allowed to remain in the validated output.
- Every mandate must point to an existing politician.

Politician schema:

```text
mp_id,first_name,last_name,birth_date,birth_place,education_level,school,academic_title,profession,languages,seniority,status,country_id
```

Mandate schema:

```text
mp_id,term,party_id,club,list,constituency,committees,mandate_start,mandate_end,election_date,votes,source_url,country_id
```

Some target fields are intentionally empty because they are not available in
the local source JSON files: `education_level`, `school`, `academic_title`,
`languages`, `list`, and `votes`.

## Party Mapping

`data/parties/party.csv` standardizes historical party and parliamentary group
labels into stable `party_id` values.

The mapping is used by:

- `convert_acteurs_to_csv.py`, for mandate group labels;
- `eda/entity_binding.py`, for speech-to-party binding.

The scripts normalize labels before matching: case, accents, punctuation,
parenthetical details, and known historical aliases are handled. Rows that
cannot be mapped safely remain empty or `P000` and are written to:

```text
deputes_boostrap/report/unresolved_party_ids.csv
```

## Sycomore Cache and Audit Reports

Sycomore HTML pages are cached in:

```text
deputes_boostrap/.sycomore_cache
```

To force a refresh:

```bash
python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py --refresh-cache
```

Audit reports are written to:

```text
deputes_boostrap/report
```

| File | Contents |
| --- | --- |
| `new_politicians.csv` | Politicians added from Sycomore because they were missing from local JSON. |
| `new_mandates.csv` | Mandates added from Sycomore because they were missing from local JSON. |
| `fallback_pa_ids.csv` | Deterministic `PA...` fallback identifiers generated from Sycomore rows. |
| `duplicate_politicians.csv` | Duplicate politicians detected during the merge. |
| `duplicate_mandates.csv` | Duplicate mandates detected during the merge. |
| `unresolved_party_ids.csv` | Mandates whose `party_id` remains empty or `P000`. |

## `data_aug.py`

`data_aug.py` has two modes:

1. Without `--deputy-url`, it delegates to the same full generation pipeline as
   `convert_acteurs_to_csv.py`.
2. With one or more `--deputy-url` arguments, it copies selected politicians
   and mandates from reference CSVs into an output directory.

Example:

```bash
python3 data_aug.py \
  --deputy-url https://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/dyn/deputes/PA123456 \
  --reference-politician-csv data/final/politician.csv \
  --reference-mandate-csv data/final/mandate.csv \
  --out-dir data/output \
  --dry-run
```

## SQL Import

The `sql/` directory contains PostgreSQL helpers:

| File | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `sql/create_tables_postgres_dbeaver.sql` | Creates tables and indexes for manual CSV import through DBeaver. |
| `sql/create_and_import_postgres.sql` | Creates tables and imports CSV files through PostgreSQL commands. |

The DBeaver workflow is:

1. run `sql/create_tables_postgres_dbeaver.sql`;
2. import the relevant CSV files through DBeaver's CSV import UI;
3. run the optional `mandate_party` population query at the end of the script
   after `mandate.csv` is imported.

## Tests and Local Checks

Run the test suite:

```bash
python3 -m pytest tests
```

Run targeted checks:

```bash
python3 -m pytest tests/test_converter_cleaning.py
python3 -m pytest tests/test_summary_extraction.py
python3 -m pytest tests/test_entity_binding.py
```

Check syntax for the main deputy script:

```bash
python3 -m py_compile convert_acteurs_to_csv.py
```

Check DILA conversion from existing local XML without downloading:

```bash
python3 main.py all --skip-download
```

Check deputy conversion without writing output files:

```bash
python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py --local-only --dry-run
```

## Compile the Report

From the repository root:

```bash
cd doc
latexmk -pdf -interaction=nonstopmode -halt-on-error dataset_report.tex
```

The generated PDF is:

```text
doc/dataset_report.pdf
```

Clean LaTeX auxiliary files while keeping the PDF:

```bash
cd doc
latexmk -c dataset_report.tex
```

## Recommended Workflow for a New User

1. Read `doc/dataset_report.pdf` for the dataset-level overview.
2. Inspect final tables in `data/final/`.
3. Run `python3 -m pytest tests` to verify the codebase locally.
4. Rebuild DILA outputs from existing XML with `python3 main.py all --skip-download`.
5. Rebuild deputy and mandate outputs safely with
   `python3 convert_acteurs_to_csv.py --local-only --dry-run`.
6. Only run network-dependent commands when you intentionally want to download
   DILA archives or refresh Sycomore data.
7. Use `sql/` scripts if the goal is to load the CSV files into PostgreSQL.

## Known Data Notes

- The final speech table covers 1998-2026.
- ParisParl is documented as covering 1996-2019, but the local processed files
  currently start in 1998.
- DILA XML is the preferred source for 2011 onward because it preserves the
  official parliamentary XML structure.
- ParisParl requires heavier cleaning because it is reconstructed from PDF
  reports.
- The final compact speech table intentionally drops rich source metadata. Use
  intermediate DILA and ParisParl files when topic hierarchy, raw text, source
  order, or source filenames are needed.
